<lj-cut text="This is not finished. But it's the Babylon Bombing fix request. Read if you want. Just warning you it's not finished or edited and if you read it you better comment and tell me if you like it or not because this is your only chance for me to change it. You have been warned. I was going to lock it, but if I have a chance to work on it it's easy for it to be public for me to get to it from any name.">
I remember watching him get ready for the event. I remember helping him button up his shirt, not because he needed my help, but because I wanted to. He fought me, come to think of it. He said "I got it Ben, Jesus Christ, finish getting yourself ready." But instead I fought him for a moment, brushing my lips against the warm skin of his chest as I buttoned up the rest of the shirt, standing back and admiring him for a moment. "What?" He cocked his head and looked at me. 

"Nothing. You're beautiful. That's all." He smiled at me for a moment before tipping his head up to catch his lips with mine. 

"We better get going. We're already running late..." I cut him off, wrapping an arm around his waist and pulling him towards me. 

"Fine. But when we get home," I raised my eyebrow and looked at him. He playfully shoved a hand against my chest and we were off. 

I can vividly remember how excited he looked when Cyndi Lauper came out unto the stage, and I can recall how he gave me a quick kiss before he moved towards the bar to get a drink for Ted and his date. 

The rest of the night wouldn't completely come back to me until months later. I could remember bits and pieces. The bright light. The smoke that permeated my lungs. The burning feeling in the back of my throat as I searched for Michael. The smell of burning flesh. The sounds of the screams. The groans. The cries for help. Months later I would sit up in the middle of the night, the sheets soaked with my sweat as I gasped for breath. This is when I would remember the specifics -  the shoes left abandoned, the blood splatters on the ground, the people taking their last breaths. The chaos that ensued the moment that the bomb exploded. 

Initially, there was nothing more important to me than finding Michael. I pushed past people, I shoved my way through the wreckage, I yelled out his name. I was searching eye level, looking for him, my shirt covering my nose and mouth as I tried to breathe. I would have never even looked down but my foot stumbled on a piece of pipe from overhead. I didn't even know it was him. But the moan, the small noise that left his mouth made my breath catch in my throat. I was horrified when I saw his face, it was completely unrecognizable. My heart broke at that precise moment.

I bent down, touching my hand softly to the top of his head, the only place that I thought was not hurt. I felt a lump in my throat that started to swell. I swallowed hard, my voice coming out shaky. "Oh, Brown Eyes." I thought I saw his eyes flutter open for a moment and his mouth moved slightly. "I'm here baby." I looked up, silently praying that I could find someone who could help. I debated whether I should pick him up and carry him myself, but I was afraid of hurting him even more - if that was possible. I blinked back the tears that were threatening to fall from my eyes. I had let him down. I promised I would always protect him. I wanted to hide him away from the world, keep him safe. And here I was, looking down at him, broken and burned. I should have gone to get that drink. 

I shook my head, clearing the thoughts and looking down at him one more time, my hand softly running along the top of his head. I felt like I had been looking at him for hours, but it must have only been seconds. I thought I saw Justin rushing past me and reached out and grabbed his arm. "Justin!" He turned and I realized it wasn't Justin as he yanked his arm around hurrying past me. That man's face would stick with me for the rest of my days, though. The fear and confusion that exuded from him snapped me back to reality. I looked down at Michael one last time and realized that I had to get him help, I didn't want to leave his side, it broke my heart even more to leave him laying there, crumbled and bleeding. 

I stood up, moving towards the door and grabbed the first paramedic that I saw and pulled him towards Michael. It wasn't until they were loading Michael unto the stretcher that I noticed the woman who was next to Michael. The paramedic that was knelt down below her shook her head at the other standing with the stretcher and they moved on. I watched as they loaded his lifeless body unto a stretcher and started to move towards the door. I followed quickly behind. I wasn't going to let him out of my sight. 

The few minutes it took to get him from the inside of Babylon to the back of the ambulance took hours, in my mind. It seemed like I replayed almost every memory we had ever shared. Every moment in time that he was in my arms. The way he looked at me that very first time I ever laid eyes on him - wide eyed and innocent with the spark in his eyes as he explained his passion for comics. The way his hand fit perfect the first time he ever grabbed for mine. The way he laid his chest on mine, our wedding rings rubbing against each other in the tent that first night we were married. His face - first thing in the morning. The way he looked at JR that first and every other time he held her in his arms. The pride that was evident in his eyes every time Hunter brought home a good grade. Even the way his entire face would light up whenever Brian used to walk into the room. At this moment, I would give anything to be leaning against the bar with Emmett and Ted, watching Michael's grin as Brian would wrap his arms around his waist as they danced. I found myself silently praying to anyone listening that I would get to experience all of these things at least one more time.

</lj-cut>
